# Coding style

## Package manager

When working in TypeScript or JavaScript, use **yarn** as the package manager. Use yarn when running tests, scripts, or executing `node_modules` binaries. Do not use npx or npm.

## No IIFEs for local values

Do **not** wrap logic in an immediately invoked function expression just to assign a local `const`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const dateRange = (() => {
  if (!selection) return {mode: 'dynamic', range: 'PAST_30_DAYS'};
  if (selection.preset === 'custom') return {mode: 'fixed', start, end};
  return {mode: 'dynamic', range: MAP[selection.preset]};
})();

// ✅ GOOD — plain control flow in the same scope
let dateRange: CreateComplianceAuditTemplateInput['dateRange'];
if (!selection) {
  dateRange = {mode: 'dynamic', range: 'PAST_30_DAYS'};
} else if (selection.preset === 'custom') {
  dateRange = {mode: 'fixed', start, end};
} else {
  dateRange = {mode: 'dynamic', range: MAP[selection.preset]};
}
```

### Allowed

- `useMemo(() => ..., [deps])` and `useCallback` — hook callbacks are not IIFEs for this rule
- IIFEs in tests or build scripts when there is a concrete reason (module scope, legacy constraint)

### When logic is reused

Extract a **named function** at module scope if it is shared. Do not use an anonymous IIFE at the call site.

## React forms: handlers, not effects

- If a user action changes one field and must update another (e.g. deselecting a location prunes selected flows), put that logic in the **triggering control's `onChange` / `onSubmit` handler** — as close as possible to the action.
- Do **not** use `useEffect` + `setValue` to react to form values the user just changed.
- `useEffect` + `setValue` is only for **async hydration** (data not available at click time) or other non-user-initiated work.
- `useWatch` + `setValue` to mirror a field's own value is an anti-pattern — bind with the form/lens API instead.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — reactive sync after user changed locations
useEffect(() => {
  setValue('selectedFlows', selectedFlows.filter(...));
}, [flowLocationIds, selectedFlows, setValue]);

// ✅ GOOD — same logic in the location multiselect handler
onChange={(nextLocations) => {
  onChange(nextLocations);
  setValue('selectedFlows', getValues('selectedFlows').filter(...));
}}
```

## useCallback

- Wrap event handlers in `useCallback` when passed to child components, render props, or listed in hook dependency arrays.
- Prefer a named `useCallback` over a large inline handler in JSX when the handler updates multiple form fields.

## useMemo for derived values

Memoize arrays, objects, and other derived values passed as **props**, listed in **hook dependency arrays**, or used as **query keys** when the source data has not changed.

Inline `.map()`, `.filter()`, object spreads, and `{...}` literals in JSX/props create a **new reference every render**. That retriggers child effects, `useList*` hooks, React Query, and memoized children even when the underlying data is unchanged.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — new array every render
<FlowSelect locationIds={selectedLocations.map((location) => location.id)} />;

// ✅ GOOD
const locationIds = useMemo(() => selectedLocations.map((location) => location.id), [selectedLocations]);

<FlowSelect locationIds={locationIds} />;
```

### Allowed without useMemo

- Primitives derived once and used inline (`selectedLocations.length`, a boolean flag)
- Values intentionally recomputed every render because the expression is cheap and nothing downstream depends on referential stability
- Literals that are not passed as props or hook deps

## File layout

Order module contents top to bottom:

1. **Public API** — exported types/interfaces, then the main exported function or component.
2. **Private module members** — non-exported types, helpers, and components used only by the public export.

Put private functions, types, and components **below** the main exported thing — never above it.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
export interface WidgetProps { ... }

export function Widget(props: WidgetProps) {
  return <WidgetBody {...props} />;
}

interface WidgetBodyProps { ... }

function WidgetBody(props: WidgetBodyProps) { ... }

// ❌ BAD — private helper above the export
function WidgetBody(props: WidgetBodyProps) { ... }

export function Widget(props: WidgetProps) { ... }
```

When a file has one exported component and a private sub-component, keep both in the same file; do **not** split into a separate file unless the user asks. The private component still goes at the bottom.

## null vs undefined

- Prefer **`null`** for intentional absence in app/form/domain types.
- Use **`undefined`** only for optional properties, optional params, and **query/API params** where omitting the key means unset.
- Nullable fields: `T | null` (required key), not optional `T?`, when the key is always present on the object.
- Absence checks: `value !== null`, not `!== undefined`, unless the type is genuinely optional.

## No single-use local variables

Do **not** declare a local variable that is referenced in only one place. Inline the expression at the use site.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — binding used once
const isQueryEnabled = enabled && Boolean(queryParams.locationIds?.length);

useQuery({
  enabled: isQueryEnabled,
});

// ✅ GOOD — inline
useQuery({
  enabled: enabled && Boolean(queryParams.locationIds?.length),
});
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const label = item.name.trim();
return <span>{label}</span>;

// ✅ GOOD
return <span>{item.name.trim()}</span>;
```

### Allowed

- Locals used **two or more times** (avoid repeating the same expression)
- Locals that exist only to give a **non-obvious** value a name where inlining would hurt readability (rare — prefer a named function if the expression is complex)
- Destructured bindings and parameters (not “declared then used once” temps)
- Hook return values kept for a stable dependency array when the same value is listed in deps

## No one-off helpers

Do **not** introduce a named function — module-scope or local — that is called from **one place only**. Inline the logic at that call site.

This applies to default-value builders, small transforms, count/format helpers, and new `export function` utilities with a single caller. If you are about to add a helper, grep for reuse first; if there is no second caller, inline it.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — helper used once
function defaultSelectedLocations(locationId: string | null) {
  if (locationId === null) return [];
  return [{ id: locationId, attributes: { name: '', ... } }];
}

defaultValues: {
  selectedLocations: defaultSelectedLocations(locationId),
}

// ✅ GOOD — inline
defaultValues: {
  selectedLocations:
    locationId === null
      ? []
      : [{ id: locationId, attributes: { name: '', address: null, city: null, state: null, zip: null } }],
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — exported utility with one caller
export function countSelectableSignInFlows(data, included, metaTotal) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — inline at the only call site inside the useMemo that needs it
if (metaTotal != null) {
  const parentGlobalCount = (included ?? []).filter(...).length;
  return metaTotal - parentGlobalCount;
}
return flows.length;
```

### Allowed

- **Private sub-components** in the same file (see File layout) — UI decomposition is not a one-off helper
- **Module-scope functions used in two or more places** in the same file or across the repo
- **Shared domain/query utilities** with multiple real callers — not "might be reused later"
